<DOCID>
900720-0115.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   AT&amp;T Earnings
   Show a 6% Drop
   For 2nd Quarter
   ---
   Revenue Declined by 2.5%;
   Net Was Hurt by Slide
   In Long-Distance Sales
   ----
   By John J. Keller
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   T
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co., hurt by a
slide in long-distance revenue and sluggish equipment sales,
said net income fell 6% in the second quarter on a 2.5% drop
in sales.
   AT&amp;T said it also paid heavily trying to keep up with
demand for its new Universal credit card, which has garnered
at least two million cardholders since its unveiling in
March.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Net fell to $657 million, or 60 cents a share, from $699
million, or 65 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue fell to
$9.03 billion from $9.26 billion.
   In the first half, net rose 2.4% to $1.33 billion, or
$1.22 a share, from $1.29 billion, or $1.20 a share, the year
before. Sales of $17.92 billion were unchanged.
   AT&amp;T's results were expected after it announced last month
that earnings would decline. Since that announcement, the
company's stock, which had been hovering in the low 40s, has
fallen to the mid-30s. In New York Stock Exchange composite
trading yesterday, AT&amp;T rose 50 cents to $37.625 on volume of
1.9 million shares.
   Despite the bland profit performance, AT&amp;T Chairman Robert
E. Allen said, "We still expect 1990 to be better than 1989,
a record earnings year. These results don't alter our
confidence in our direction or our future prospects."
   Included in the results were charges of about $100 million
to cover consolidations, layoffs and other costs in AT&amp;T's
services businesses, including long-distance and maintenance
and installation.
   AT&amp;T also took a charge of about $290 million to cover
consolidations and personnel reallocations in microelectronic
parts and systems and for reclaiming scrap metal.
   All this was offset by a credit of $400 million, which
came from a net reduction in the reserves set up in December
1988 associated with modernization of AT&amp;T's network. AT&amp;T
attributed the reduction to lower removal and disposal costs
of obsolete equipment. The company said the reduction would
have been even greater if not for increased costs from force
reductions and facilities closings.
   Sales of equipment continued to be hurt by a slowdown in
the business market. While sales of switching and
transmission equipment to phone companies inched ahead 1.8%
to $1.8 billion, other equipment sales suffered. Business,
data and consumer equipment revenue fell 11% to $1.7 billion.
AT&amp;T doesn't break out its profit for its equipment
businesses, but analysts estimate the company is losing more
than $300 million a year on office phone systems and computer
equipment.
   On the services side, long-distance revenue fell 3.9% to
$4.8 billion from $5.02 billion. AT&amp;T attributed the decline
to $100 million in additional payments to the local phone
companies for completing long-distance calls over their local
networks, and a shift by an undisclosed number of business
customers to newer, lower-priced communications services.
   Still, Morris Tanenbaum, AT&amp;T vice chairman and chief
financial officer, was optimistic about long-distance
operations. He noted that AT&amp;T's traffic volume grew 7%, an
indication that it has begun to stanch a loss of business to
its primary competitors, MCI Communications Corp. and US
Sprint Communications Co., a unit of United
Telecommunications Inc.
   "We don't see any decrease in overall strength of the
market, said Mr. Tanenbaum. "And our profitability remains
strong."
   Jack Grubman, analyst at PaineWebber Inc., said the
quarter "was probably better than expected," given that
product sales decreased a meager 2% in a very tough pricing
environment and "their margins of 43% are the highest they've
been in three years." Moreover, he said AT&amp;T's long-distance
volume grew 15% to 20% in the small-business arena, where MCI
and Sprint have experienced sluggishness.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900720-0114
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900720-0114.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Measure Aimed at Shifting Regulation
   Of Index Futures to SEC Is in Trouble
   ----
   By Kevin G. Salwen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C20
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)
CONGRESS (CNG)
COMMODITY FUTURES TRADING COMMISSION (CFT)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The administration's bill to shift power to
the Securities and Exchange Commission from commodities
regulators is in severe trouble, and key backers in the
Senate are scrambling to find a compromise.
   When the bill comes before the Senate, probably later this
year, it may not include a provision to shift oversight of
stock-index futures to the SEC from the Commodity Futures
Trading Commission. That's partly because heavy lobbying by
the futures industry and what critics consider a weak push by
the administration has failed to convince most senators of
the provision's usefulness. Moreover, some senators believe
the current regulatory structure is better for the futures
markets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Administration officials, led by Treasury Secretary
Nicholas Brady and SEC Chairman Richard Breeden, contend that
the split regulatory clout of the SEC and CFTC encourages
stock-market volatility and hurts enforcement efforts. The
SEC oversees stocks and options, and the CFTC regulates
stock-index futures.
   Those futures, which are primarily used by large
institutional investors for hedging purposes, allow investors
to bet on the movement of a basket of stocks without owning
the shares. They are frequently used in computerized program
trading strategies.
   Sen. John Heinz (R., Pa.), a staunch supporter of the
administration's bill, said he is seeking a "compromise that
will solve the major issues."
   Another backer, Sen. Timothy Wirth (D., Colo.), said he
was "disappointed" by the administration's efforts on behalf
of the bill. "I don't see any great momentum here," he said.
"The case hasn't been very well made by the administration."
   Some Senate aides fear that negotiations over a compromise
are hurting the bill's chances because they indicate a lack
of support for the administration's proposal. Several aides
even noted that draft proposals without an index-futures
shift are in the works.
   A Treasury official denied that the administration's
efforts have been weak and said Mr. Brady strongly supports
all parts of the bill.
   "Some people have been offering compromises from the
beginning," the official said. "We think the administration's
proposal is what needs to be done." He added: "There's
obviously very strong opposition on the other side. It's a
jurisdiction issue: Those are the toughest issues on the
Hill."
   Vote counts show that the bill would have a tough time
passing if the Senate voted today. But a huge number of
senators haven't made a decision about the administration's
proposal. A compromise clearly would give them two benefits.
First, it would relieve the senators of having to learn the
nuances of complex markets, and second, it would allow them
to tell constituents that they voted against volatility.
   The draft bills specifically focus on one of the
administration bill's key proposalsgranting oversight of
futures margins to a federal agency. Currently, margins --
the good-faith money needed to trade futures -- are set by
the exchanges and can't be changed by the CFTC or any
regulator except in emergencies. Messrs. Breeden and Brady
contend that low margins in the futures markets helped
exacerbate the market drops of October 1987 and October 1989.
They contend that unless federal oversight of margins is
ordered by Congress, the futures exchanges will once again
bring them down to what Mr. Breeden calls "dangerously low
levels."
   Mr. Breeden appears to be focusing almost exclusively on
the margin question. In testimony yesterday before the Senate
Banking Committee, Mr. Breeden repeatedly decried "excess
leverage" in the futures markets that he said threatened the
stock investments of 50 million Americans.
   Senate staffers said the compromise measure also will
focus on a clause in the Commodity Exchange Act that requires
any new product with elements of futures contracts to be
traded on a futures exchange and regulated by the CFTC.
   Sen. Wirth also criticized the White House's renomination
of Wendy Gramm as CFTC chairman. "The single most important
statement they are making is reappointing the person" who
most staunchly opposes a shift of jurisdiction, he said.
   In his testimony yesterday, Mr. Breeden expressed caution
about the proposed stock transfer excise tax, which would put
a 0.15% surcharge on the sale of investments. Although it
hasn't been brought up at the summit table, the proposal is
one of several being discussed by the administration and
Capitol Hill leaders currently negotiating budget accords.
   Mr. Breeden refused to criticize the excise tax
explicitly, but he told senators, "We have to be
extraordinarily careful in creating taxes on capital
formation." Saying that U.S. securities taxes are higher than
those in many other countries, Mr. Breeden said he is
concerned about taking "steps to drive trading offshore."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900720-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900720-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   The Americas:
   The Shining Path Fights On in Peru
   ----
   By Gustavo Gorriti
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A13
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM
</CO>
<LP>
   LIMA -- On June 4, I was among a group of journalists who
were told that the war against the Shining Path ("Sendero
Luminoso") guerrillas had almost been won. Lucky punches
sometimes win wars, and maybe this was the case. We had been
allowed into a "safe house" that, according to Interior
Minister Agustin Mantilla, had been used as headquarters by
the leaders of the Marxist guerrilla movement. The police had
discovered the house in one of Lima's affluent neighborhoods
just two days earlier. This was the underground
organization's central nervous system, commented
investigative Police Chief Fernando Reyes Roca, a short man
who is a consummate bureaucratic survivor. Interior Ministry
spokesman Fernando Yavera joked that this find was going to
put Shining Path watchers (such as myself) out of business.
   Alas, as it turned out this was not the rebel
organization's headquarters, nor its central nervous system,
but more of an archive and memorabilia repository.
Nevertheless, it was a very important and unexpected police
coup against the Shining Path -- one that probably could have
brought dramatic results if President Alan Garcia had not
decided to make public the operation so soon after the first
police intervention, in order to score a quick propaganda
gain. This impulsiveness gave full warning to the guerrillas'
entire clandestine apparatus, allowing them to limit
considerably the damage inflicted on them.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As Alberto Fujimori prepares to take over as Peru's next
president on July 28, the question of whether the Shining
Path will hound his administration as it has the previous two
ranks high among his concerns. Among Shining Path watchers
("Senderlogos") there is strong disagreement on fundamentals:
Is the Shining Path getting stronger or weaker? Is it making
progress or losing ground among the population? And finally,
who is actually winning the war? There are no easy answers.
   There is not much of a dispute on the basic data, however.
The Shining Path went to war in 1980, on the same day Peru
was holding general elections after 12 years of a military
dictatorship. Its first actions were cautious, modest and
often ludicrous in a crazy way (like hanging dogs from
lampposts, with scribbled insults over them to Chinese
Communist martyrs). But the actions intensified and soon
became quite lethal.
   While President Fernando Belaunde's regime did what it
could to maintain democratic legality at first, it was quite
unprepared to deal with any insurgency -- especially with one
that had been meticulously planned and organized several
years before the first shot was fired.
   In October 1981, emergency laws were imposed for the first
time on part of Peru; they covered only 2% of the population.
Now about 50% of all Peruvians live under emergency law. In
10 years, the war between the Shining Path and the government
has cost about 20,000 lives. Damages are estimated at $16
billion, or about 85% of Peru's annual gross national
product.
   If the armed forces have been rightly accused of
systematic violations of human rights (Peru ranks as one of
the world's worst human-rights offenders), the military
faults the civilian authorities for failing to provide
much-needed leadership. Mr. Belaunde (the first to deal with
the problem), who tried to ignore the insurgency out of
existence, is regarded as a well-meaning but inept leader.
   There are no kind words for Mr. Garcia, on the other hand.
In the first weeks of his mandate, he made several right
moves -- like emphasizing his role as commander in chief of
the armed forces and reorganizing the corruption-ridden
police. But things began to unravel soon after. At first, he
tried a liberal approach, looking for a dialogue with the
fanatical Shining Path, and sending scores of young
professionals to the emergency areas to attack what he said
were the "root causes" of the insurgency. But dialogue was
disdainfully rejected: Dozens of these professionals were
assassinated, and the armed forces slowed down their actions,
while the rebels made largely unimpeded progress.
   Then, Mr. Garcia tried a tougher approach, and
human-rights violations surged to their current level. And
for the first time, death squads -- linked by some analysts
to Mr. Garcia's APRA Party -- began to contribute to the
killing. Midpoint during his term, Mr. Garcia lost all hope
of defeating the Shining Path, and decided just to coexist
with it, says Rafael Merino, a respected analyst on security
matters.
   Not even in that was Mr. Garcia successful, as violence
climbed steadily during the second half of his term. In 1988,
1,986 people were killed as a result of insurgent or
counterinsurgent actions; in 1989, 3,198 were killed; and
1,730 during the first six months of 1990.
   How well is Mr. Fujimori expected to deal with the
insurgency? His campaign pitch advocated an approach closely
resembling that of Mr. Garcia's first year. According to
Francisco Loayza, Mr. Fujimori's adviser on internal-security
matters, military actions against the Shining Path should be
subordinated to economic-development initiatives. "{The
military} should mainly provide security for development
projects," Mr. Loayza says. He stressed that the main thrust
of Mr. Fujimori's "pacification" policies would be to address
the "structural violence {read: social injustice} that makes
subversion possible." Mr. Loayza says that President Garcia's
approach failed because of corruption and ineptitude. He also
feels that the Shining Path is weakened, and that an
important Shining Path faction would be willing to engage in
peace talks.
   This is only wishful thinking, according to Mr. Merino:
"If President Fujimori thinks he'll finish the war through
those `pacification' policies, it will be like riding into
battle with no better dress or weapons than a tuxedo."
   Actually, Mr. Fujimori might end up implementing internal
war policies that would be quite different from those
advocated during his campaign. At least, that's what seems is
going to happen with the economy, where the vote-getting
populist message appears in the process of being replaced by
a far more orthodox approach. Free-market economist Hernando
de Soto, who has been advising Mr. Fujimori during the past
month, thinks that might be the case. "He learns fast," Mr.
de Soto told me recently, "and he has all the right
instincts."
   Even if Mr. Fujimori proves to be a quick learner, he will
have his work cut out for him. Running against all major
trends of contemporary history, the insurgents have followed
Shining Path founder Abimael Guzman with the commitment that
the faithful reserve for their prophet. This was evident when
walking through their safe house in Lima. It looked, said a
Peruvian journalist, like the seed for the future "Museum of
the Revolution" -- wood carvings; woven baskets; tapestries;
paintings; chiseled stone; all meticulously, lovingly crafted
with the mythified motifs of the internal war. There were
also the hagiographic representations of Mr. Guzman himself,
in the various postures that endeavored to combine the heroic
with the intellectual. A whole closed, inbred culture,
developed in the underground and unnoticed by most Peruvians
-- except when it explodes in their faces.
   ---
   Mr. Gorriti is a Peruvian author and journalist.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
