<HL>
   NHI Nelson Holdings
   Makes Staff Changes
   In Nelson Subsidiary
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4E
</SO>
<CO>
   NNH T.NNH WNEWS
</CO>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- NHI Nelson Holdings International Ltd.
announced several senior executive changes, including staff
cuts, in its Nelson Entertainment Group as part of its
previously announced restructuring plan to focus on making
and marketing movies.
   The company's shares fell 75 cents to $4.375 in composite
trading yesterday on the American Stock Exchange.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The company issued a statement saying it believed the
staff cuts had been "misinterpreted."
   Nelson said it decided to consolidate its international
sales and marketing operations in its London office. Massimo
Graziosi was named president and chief operating officer of
the group's Nelson Entertainment International, a sales and
marketing arm. He was formerly senior vice president of the
unit.
   He succeeds Ian Jessel, who held the same title but at
Nelson's offices in Los Angeles. The company said Mr. Jessel
resigned after learning that Nelson planned to move the
operations to London. Nelson also said that Ian Scorer,
executive vice president of Nelson Entertainment
International in London, also resigned. Messrs. Jessel and
Scorer couldn't be reached for comment.
   The company also said that Steve Sohmer resigned as
president of Nelson Television, another unit of Nelson
Entertainment Group. The company said it will de-emphasize
its operations in television development and production.
   Nelson Entertainment Group is one of a dwindling number of
independent movie producers. The company co-produced the
highly successful "When Harry Met Sally" and released "Bill
and Ted's Excellent Adventure." The company has seven movies
in the pipeline including "The Taking of Beverly Hills," a
movie in which all the homes and stores in Beverly Hills are
robbed.
   Analysts note that the executive changes and the
restructuring follow the company's loss in the first quarter,
reflecting a dearth of releases. "The company is trying to
recapitalize its financial balance sheet and this is a
good-faith effort to lower the overhead as much as they can,"
said Jeff Logsdon, senior vice president of Seidler Amdec
Securities in Los Angeles.
   NHI Holdings also holds a 69% stake Nelson Vending
Technology. In the first quarter of this year, NHI Holdings
reported a net loss of $3.2 million on revenues of $18.9
million, compared with a net loss of $4.8 million on revenues
of $16.3 million in the year-earlier quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900720-0092
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900720-0092.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Navistar Weighs
   Making an Offer
   For Mack Trucks
   ----
   By Richard Koenig and James P. Miller
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   MACK NAV F.RNA
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
LAND TRANSPORTATION EQUIPMENT (LDT)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Navistar International Corp. is considering a bid for Mack
Trucks Inc. that would compete with one already under way
from Renault Vehicules Industriels S.A.
   Renault Vehicules already owns a 45% Mack stake, and it
recently launched a $6-a-share, or $99 million, tender offer
for the 55% of the Allentown, Pa., truck maker it doesn't
currently control.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Navistar, among the U.S.'s biggest truck manufacturers,
approached a committee of Mack's directors to express
interest in a possible bid that would exceed Renault's offer.
   However, Navistar said it couldn't proceed with an offer
unless Renault decided to dispose of its interest in Mack, an
action Renault said in a news release that it "has no
interest" in taking.
   Moreover, the truck-making unit of Regie Nationale des
Usines Renault could increase its stake in Mack to 61% from
45% by exercising a warrant and converting certain debentures
it owns.
   In Allentown, a Mack spokesman declined to comment beyond
the joint statement with Renault. Officials at Renault, based
in Paris, couldn't be reached for comment.
   Navistar confirmed that it had made the overture and said
it will need to make a comprehensive due-diligence
examination of Mack "to determine whether to make a firm
offer and a specific per-share price."
   The Chicago-based truck and diesel-engine maker declined
to elaborate on its possible interest in financially strapped
Mack.
   Mack's board, four of whose nine members are Renault
officials, hasn't responded to Renault's offer. Renault has
said it wants to take full ownership of the company because
of Mack's deteriorating condition and the need to refinance
its debt.
   Yesterday, Mack, which still faces a sagging market for
its heavy-duty trucks, reported that it had a loss of $63.3
million, or $2.13 a share, in the second quarter on sales of
$400.9 million. In national over-the-counter trading, Mack
common closed unchanged at $7.125. The Mack statement came
out after the market closed.
   Like Mack, Navistar has seen sales and earnings suffer
from a deep industry slump. In its first quarter, ended Jan.
31, it had a loss of $18 million, or 10 cents a share;
second-quarter earnings were down 77% at $8 million, or one
cent a share. Its six-month sales were off 11% at $1.81
billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
