<HL>
   Business Brief -- Commonwealth Edison Co.:
   Utility Reports Net Loss,
   Spurred by Court Charges
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   CWE
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   Commonwealth Edison Co., Chicago, hurt by special charges
associated with two recent adverse court rulings, reported a
second-quarter net loss of $378.4 million, or $1.88 a share.
In the year-ago period, the utility had net income of $152.6
million, or 61 cents a share.
   Revenues, adjusted to reflect court-ordered rate cuts,
fell to $846.4 million from $1.31 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A rate rollback and refund, ordered by the Illinois
Supreme Court in May, generated an after-tax provision of
$253 million, or $1.19 a share.
   Disallowances and a refund ordered in June by the Illinois
Appellate Court, concerning Commonwealth's Byron 1 nuclear
plant, required a charge of $208 million, or 98 cents a
share, in the latest quarter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900720-0059
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900720-0059.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Apache Corp. to Post
   Profit Increase of 67%
   For Second Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4G
</SO>
<CO>
   APA
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   DENVER -- Apache Corp. expects to report second-quarter
net income rose 67% to about $7.5 million, or 17 cents a
share, from $4.5 million, or 14 cents a share, a year
earlier, said Raymond Plank, chairman and chief executive
officer.
   Attributing the record second-quarter results to increased
natural gas production and reduced costs, Mr. Plank said
six-month net income increased 92% to about $19 million, or
43 cents a share, from $9.9 million, or 30 cents a share, a
year earlier. Shares outstanding as of June 30 averaged about
44.6 million, reflecting a 35% increase from 33 million a
year ago. The company is expected to report its earnings next
week.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Mr. Plank said revenue for the second quarter is expected
to match the year-earlier's $59 million. Six-month revenue
rose about 5% to $127 million from $120.6 million.
   Apache's natural gas production during the quarter
increased about 15% to 260 million cubic feet a day from 227
million cubic feet.
   With oil prices off slightly from a year ago, Mr. Plank
said second-quarter oil production was "close to flat"
compared with 1989 when Apache produced about 8,600 barrels a
day.
   Mr. Plank said Apache had recorded about a 25% reduction
in lease operating, administrative and financing costs during
the first six months, much of it because of the conversion of
two debenture issues, which resulted in a savings in interest
costs of about $1 million a month.
   Because of Apache's performance during the first six
months, Mr. Plank said, "we do not have basis to disagree"
with analysts' estimates that per-share earnings for 1990
will be 75 cents to 80 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
