<HL>
   Business Brief -- E.W. Scripps Co.:
   Scripps Howard to Purchase
   WMAR-TV of Baltimore
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3
</SO>
<CO>
   EWSCA
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   Scripps Howard Broadcasting Co., an 80%-owned subsidiary
of the E.W. Scripps Co., said it has agreed to purchase
WMAR-TV in Baltimore from the Gillett Group Inc. for $154.7
million.
   The station, an affiliate of National Broadcasting Co.,
which is a unit of General Electric Co., recently signed a
new three-year contract to continue as the flagship station
for the Baltimore Orioles baseball team.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Gillett Group is controlled by George N. Gillett Jr.,
who for several years has been trying to sell his TV stations
to pay off junk-bond debt. Mr. Gillett, a Denver businessman,
also controls SCI Television Inc., which has had to
restructure $1.3 billion in debt.
   Lawrence A. Leser, president and chief executive officer
of E.W. Scripps, said the company has not made a major
acquisition since 1986, "preferring to wait until an
attractive opportunity presented itself."
   Cincinnati-based Scripps Howard Broadcasting currently
operates nine television stations.
</TEXT>
