<HL>
   Integrated Wins
   Order Blocking
   CRI's Purchase Bid
   ----
   By Robin Goldwyn Blumenthal
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4B
</SO>
<CO>
   IRE CMM AIMBZ AIMAZ
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- A federal judge overseeing Integrated
Resources Inc.'s bankruptcy-law proceeding temporarily
blocked efforts by CRI Inc. to buy four real estate
investment partnerships managed by Integrated.
   At a hearing in U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Judge Howard C.
Buschman III granted Integrated's request for a preliminary
injunction delaying two lawsuits CRI filed in Delaware and
California state courts against Integrated -- which manages
more than 600 partnerships -- in connection with CRI's
proposed bid for the partnership interests. CRI is seeking to
gain control of the interests by approaching the investors in
the limited partnerships directly, outside a court-approved
auction process to sell the interests.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The order effectively gives Integrated, which has an
agreement pending to sell its interests in the partnerships
directly to Krupp Cos., until Aug. 1 to "straighten out the
deal with Krupp," Judge Buschman said. The judge indicated a
condition that was added to the agreement with Krupp after
CRI announced its bid would have to be addressed.
   Although Judge Buschman said "it would be a detriment to
other bidders {in the auction} to renegotiate the terms after
the bids are in," he said it would be "appropriate" to
address the limited issue of renegotiating that condition.
   As part of the court-approved auction, Integrated agreed
June 7 to sell its general partner interests in its American
Insured Mortgage Investors series of limited partnerships to
Krupp for $45 million. But after CRI's bid was announced, a
condition was added to Integrated's agreement with Krupp that
CRI's proposal be ended and its lawsuits dropped. Integrated
announced that accord June 15.
   However, on June 12, CRI, a real estate syndicator based
in Rockville, Md., filed a proposal with the Securities and
Exchange Commission to offer to swap interests in two of its
real estate ventures for the AIM partnership interests.
   Allan M. Pepper, an attorney for Integrated, argued that
CRI's actions would undermine Integrated's efforts at
reorganization and the auction process. He said the company
now will move to develop "a strategy toward a closing with
Krupp."
   Stephen D. Weinroth, Integrated chairman, said the company
plans to seek a permanent injunction to block CRI's proposed
exchange offer. Mr. Weinroth said Integrated was encouraged
by the judge's statements "that the facts presented raised
the inference that CRI may have intentionally interfered"
with the court-approved auction.
   Larry Gerber, president of Krupp, said it plans to "go
forward" and that Krupp has had discussions with Integrated
about an amendment to the purchase accord.
   Attorneys for CRI wouldn't comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900720-0033
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900720-0033.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canada's Bombardier,
   Family Agree to Issue
   7.5 Million Shares
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BBD.A
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
</IN>
<LP>
   MONTREAL -- Bombardier Inc. said it and members of the
Bombardier family agreed to issue 7.5 million common shares
to the public for a total of about 146.3 million Canadian
dollars (US$126.3 million).
   The company said it will offer five million Class B
subordinated voting shares, and the Bombardier family will
sell 2.5 million Class B shares, all at C$19.50 a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bombardier said proceeds of about C$93 million from the
company's sale of the five million newly issued shares will
be used to reduce debt and to increase working capital.
   At last report, Bombardier had total debt of about C$222
million and C$504 million in shareholders' equity. Some
analysts said they had not expected the company to issue more
equity.
   The transportation equipment manufacturer has made several
major acquisitions in recent months, including the $75
million purchase of Learjet Corp. from Integrated Resources
Inc. announced in April.
   The Bombardier family's voting control of the company
doesn't appear likely to be affected by their sale of the
shares. At last report, the family held 78.7% of the Class A
shares, representing a voting stake of 67%.
   A preliminary prospectus is expected to be filed with
regulators Monday. The share issue is subject to board and
regulatory approvals. Toronto-based securities dealer Scotia
McLeod Inc. will be the issue's lead underwriter.
   In trading on the Toronto Stock Exchange yesterday,
Bombardier's Class B shares closed at C$19.75, down 62.5
Canadian cents. Its Class A shares closed at C$19.875, down
50 Canadian cents.
</TEXT>
