<HL>
   Program Trading Is 10.9%
   Of NYSE Volume in Week
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C16
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Program trading accounted for 10.9% of New
York Stock Exchange volume, or 13.6 million shares a day, in
the week ended July 6.
   That was down from 13.7% the previous week, the Big Board
said in its weekly report on the computer-aided trading
strategies.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The biggest program traders during the week, accounting
for 66% of all program trading on the exchange, were General
Electric Co.'s Kidder, Peabody Group Inc. (10.2 million
shares), Morgan Stanley Group Inc. (8.2 million), Merrill
Lynch &amp; Co. (6.1 million), Salomon Inc.'s Salomon Brothers
(5.9 million) and Susquehanna Investment Group (5.6 million).
   Program trading is the purchase or sale of a group of at
least 15 and often hundreds of different stocks. Stock-index
arbitrage, which accounted for 45% of all program trading in
the week ended July 6, involves stock purchases and sales
with offsetting trades in futures and options.
   Kidder, Morgan, Salomon and Susquehanna accounted for
about 76% of all stock-index arbitrage for the week.
</TEXT>
