<HL>
   Business Brief -- Textron Inc.:
   Firm Reports a 22% Increase
   In Second-Quarter Earnings
</HL>
<DATE>
07/20/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C18
</SO>
<CO>
   TXT
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Textron Inc., citing continued strength in its financial
services segment and lower costs on fixed-price contracts,
said second-quarter profit rose 22% to $72.1 million, or 80
cents a share.
   In the 1989 second quarter, when the Providence, R.I.,
company was hurt by a $9.5 million extraordinary loss, net
income was $59.3 million, or 67 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Revenue for the period rose 11% to $2 billion from $1.8
billion.
   B.F. Dolan, chairman and chief executive, said that while
some of Textron's markets remain soft, the company's
diversity enabled it to achieve a "good" first half. Mr.
Dolan predicted that 1990 "should be another good year for
Textron."
   For the six months, Textron reported net of $138.3
million, or $1.53 a share, on revenue of $3.9 billion. In the
year-ago period, the company had net of $122.6 million, or
$1.40 a share, on revenue of $3.7 billion.
   Textron is a financial services, aerospace and commercial
products concern.
